They need the political acceptance that is brought about by a redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social security systems.
And all of this applies just as much to global markets.
2. For the foreseeable future, democratic state leadership is likely to be largely organized within national political communities.
The national state continues to exist, even if it may be weakening, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The striving for a world government is futile exertion.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments would cede significant control authority to transnational institutions; furthermore, harmonizing rules would not benefit societies with differing needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis appears to illustrate it more instead.
We often squander international cooperation on excessively ambitious goals. As a result, we end up with weak outcomes that represent the lowest common denominator between the major powers.
When international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel Rules on capital requirements and the World Trade Organization's rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures characterize this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes in our own countries, rather than destroying them.
