3. Pluralistic Prosperity: The admission that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best suit their needs.
The United States, Europe, and Japan have, when viewed over the long term, produced comparable levels of prosperity.
However, their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – with a different one every decade – is then presented as the great success that one should emulate.
The most successful companies of the future will allow space for experiments and permit another evolution of their institutions.
A global economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will promote such a willingness to experiment and evolutionary development rather than suppress them.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing观点支持者的意见。
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools to design and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries retain national rules - such as tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect public health and consumer safety - and that they may do so by erecting barriers at their borders when trade is demonstrably threatening local practices that enjoy broad public support.
If the proponents of globalization are correct, the call for such protective measures due to lack of evidence or support will fail.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve so that, in the public debates, values standing in opposition to each other – the benefits of open world economies and the benefits of maintaining national regulations – can both be heard appropriately.
5. No country has the right to impose its own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in finance to maintain values and rules within one's own country should not be confused with using them to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a manner that is found unacceptable by most citizens in these countries.
However, they should not allow the USA or the EU to use trade sanctions or other leverage to change labor market regulations, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to difference, not to forced convergence.
