6. International economic agreements for regulating interactions between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic functions of global economic governance does not mean that we should forego international rules.
The Bretton Woods system eventually also had clear rules, albeit ones that were limited in scope and depth.
A complete catch-as-catch-can would benefit nobody.
What we need are trade rules for the world economy that help different-sized, shaped, and speed vehicles navigate each other, instead of prescribing identical cars or uniform speed limits.
We should strive to achieve a maximum level of globalization that is in line with the preservation of room for diversity regarding national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot count on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where such consultations actually take place within the national states.
If states are not democratic, this framework falls apart.
We cannot then assume any longer that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Thus, undemocratic states must therefore be subject to less liberal rules.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
The most important thing is that they must accept the ultimate paradox each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when it is not taken to extremes.
